\begin_layout Standard
New high-energy experiments, future experimental proposals, and computational
 tools are expected to enhance the knowledge of the nucleon structure.
 However, the global analysis that assesses their impact on Parton Distribution
 Functions (PDFs) knowledge is computationally expensive due to the correspondin
g large size of data.
 I developed a new approach that can make a quickly preliminary evaluation
 to help the analysis process.
 It quantifies the impact of hadronic experiments on PDFs based on Hessian
 correlation and quality of measurements.
 This approach is accessible through an open source software called PDFSense.
 I use PDFSense and other statistical methods to evaluate the impact of
 the latest Large Hadron Collider (LHC) datasets on PDFs.
 In addition, I use this software to investigate the synergy of lattice
 calculations and 
