\begin_layout Standard
The standard model (SM) explains the interaction between matter and matter
 in the universe.
 Under the SM structure, there are 25 kinds of particles and corresponding
 three kinds of interactions in the universe, namely, strong force, weak
 force, electromagnetic force, The four gravitational forces have not been
 successfully integrated into the SM framework.
 The electromagnetic force describes the interaction between charged particles,
 and the weak force describes the atomic decay of subatomic particles.
 Strong force describes the interaction among colored particles, that is,
 the interaction between particles in the nucleus.
 The gravitational force describes the rules of celestial body movement
 and many phenomena on the ground, such as free fall motion and projectile
 motion.
 Confirmation of the W and Z bosons (1983), top quark (1995), the tau neutrino
 (2000), and the Higgs boson (2012) confirm the ability of SM to interpret
 the physical world.
 Among them, quantum chromodynamics (QCD) is the theory of quarks and gluon
 in SM.
 In this theory, gluon is responsible for transferring strong force between
 quarks.
 The relationship between quarks and gluon can be analogized to the relationship
 between electrons and photons.
 The difference between them is QCD is a quantum field theory of SU(3) symmetry,
 that is, three color charges carried by quarks represent three degrees
 of freedoms of SU(3) and gluon is the corresponding gauge field.
 (a) QCD predicts that quarks and gluons will not exist alone, but only
 bound into a particle called hadron, referring to particles consisting
 of two or three quarks.
 QCD's interpretation of this bound particle is that the coupling between
 them becomes stronger with the energy scale.
 When hadron collided, the quark that was knocked out produced a strong
 dependence on the coupling, which made it more stable to make another quark
 from the vacuum to set it up.
 This phenomenon is usually called asymtotic freedom.
 Due to the asymtotic freedom relationship, above about 1 GeV, this bound
 structure is difficult to predict with perturbation theory.
 Above this energy, we assuming in collision processes, quarks and gluons
 in hadron are non-interacting.
 In this hypothesis, in hadron scattering processes, the probability of
 various quarks participating in the collision is independent of processes.
 We can use the probability function to describe quarks and gluon as function
 of momentum fraction and factorization scale.
 We call such a function Parton Distribution Functions (PDFs).
 PDFs are important models for studying hadron scattering processes, and
 the theoretical predictions of these processes depend on our knowledge
 of these functions.
 Taking Deep Inelastic Scattering (DIS) process 
\begin_inset Formula $ep\rightarrow eX$
\end_inset

 as an example, its cross section could be expressed as following: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{tot}=\underset{a}{\sum}\int dxf_{a/p}(x,\mu)\sigma_{ea\rightarrow eX}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 refers to quark and gluon and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a/p}(x,\mu)$
\end_inset

 is PDFs for various quarks and gluon.
 This relation tells us that the theoretical prediction of hadron collision
 processes could be divided into two independent parts: PDFs part and and
 the hard scattering 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{ea\rightarrow eX}(x)$
\end_inset

 which we can derive from Feynman diagram.
\end_layout

